To draw the histograms and boxplots for the univariate analysis, I am going to make use of a handy function that Jitendra gave us during the MLS sessions where the two plots are drawn as subplots one on top of the other.¶

In [62]:
# This code has been adapted from the code that Jitendra presented during the MLS sessions.
# Original credit for this function goes to Jitendra.
#
# This allows for the display of a histogram as well as box plot of the same feature for univariate analysis.

def showHistBox(feature, figsize=(15, 10), bins=None):
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="green"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.displot(
        feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        np.mean(feature), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        np.median(feature), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

For some of the next set of analysis, I will adapt a function given to us by Jitendra during the MLS sessions that plots a stacked chart. I have made the function more generic.

In [71]:
### Function to plot stacked bar charts for categorical columns
def stacked_plot(x, y, sorting_value):
    sns.set()
    ## crosstab 
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x,y,margins=True).sort_values(by=sorting_value,ascending=False)
    print(tab1)
    print('-'*120)
    ## visualising the cross tab
    tab = pd.crosstab(x,y,normalize='index').sort_values(by=sorting_value,ascending=False)
    tab.plot(kind
             ='bar',stacked=True,figsize=(17,7))
    plt.legend(loc='lower left', frameon=False,)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1,1))
    plt.show()

Family size¶

It is apparent that the bigger family size of 3 and 4 are the people who tend to accept personal loans more often. This seems reasonable since when you have children, their educational and other needs may cause additional monetary needs and this leads to personal loans. It is possible that there are other needs like home improvement, etc. for larger families that lead to personal loans.

We do not have data to see what other factors might influence larger families to need more personal loans.

However, the bank probably should target individuals with family size of 3-4 to sell more personal loans.

Summary of EDA¶

  • The data set for this project is quite clean and requires minimal data cleanup and feature engineering.
  • We need to drop the ID column and the Experience columns from the data.
  • Age and Experience have similar distribution of data and is normal distribution.
  • Age and Experience have a very strong correlation (0.99), hence we have decided to drop Experience as a feature.
  • Income distribution is right skewed, as expected, and has a few outliers. But they don't appear to be far out enought that anything needs to be dropped.

Bivariate analysis showed the following things intuitively

  • Higher income people are more likely to take out personal loans.
  • More educated people (higher degrees or professionals) tend to take loans.
  • Presence of securities account doesn't appear to sway people one way or another when taking personal loans.
  • Online banking pattern doesn't seem to have much influence on taking personal loans.
  • Having a CD account may reduce likelihood of taking personal loans.
  • Mortgages don't appear to have a direct impact by themselves in making personal loans more likely. The data set has few mortgages and there are plenty of outliers, so it is difficult to interpret.

Feature Engineering and Data Cleanup¶

In [83]:
# First let's drop the columns that are not going to be useful for our anaysis.

# Drop ID since it has no relevance on the analysis
# Drop Experience since it has a very strong (0.99) correlation with Age
# Drop CCAvg since it has a strong (0.65) correlation with Income

Logistic Regressions¶

Goal of the predictions¶

Before we build the model and start doing the logistic regression, we need to be clear about what measures are most important to us.

We aim to give suggestion to bank on who is likely to be attracted to personal loans product, hence we will recommend going after those people - through advertisement, fliers, follow-ups, etc. That means that there is an investment the bank will need to make for people we identify as potential customers.

It is more important that our predictions of Positives be as accurate as possible. That means we have to focus more on the Precision (TP/(TP+FP)). Our goal is to get a high number for the precision.¶

In this case, Recall doesn't matter as much because even if we predict someone as Negative, but they end up buying a product, the bank did not invest in targeting those customers and got them for free.

Accuracy doesn't matter as much since we are not too concerned about the negative predictions.

Our goal will be to get a model with a high precision.¶

In [156]:
def showScores(y_actual, y_pred, type="Training") :
    '''
    A utility function to display the scores for either a test set or for a training set.
    Caller should send predicted and actual Y values for either a test set or for a training set, but not both.
    '''
    accuracy = metrics.accuracy_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    precision = metrics.precision_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    recall = metrics.recall_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    
    print(type + " Set >>>>")
    print(f"       Accuracy: {accuracy}")
    print(f"       Recall: {recall}")
    print(f"       Precision: {precision}")
    print(f"       F1: {f1}")
In [157]:
# This code has been adapted from code provided with the lectures.
def showConfusionMatrix(y_actual, y_pred) :
    '''
    A utility function to show the confusion matrix as a heat map. A caller should provide the predicted and
    actual Y values for either a training set or for a test set, but not both.
    '''
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_actual, y_pred, labels=[1, 0])

    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual True","Actual False"]],
                         columns = [i for i in ["Predict True","Predict False"]])
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='')

Observation and Interpretation.¶

The model appears to be a fairly good one as it provides a pretty high number for precision for both the training data (0.84) as well as the test data (0.82). This is a fairly reliable model and can be used target customers.

There is a little bit of overfitting going on because the precision on the test data is slighly lower than the results on the training data, but the difference is just 2%.

The following coefficients are positive

  • Income, Family, Education, Mortgage, CD_Account
  • This means that a higher income, family size, or education level leads to higher chances of taking personal loan.
  • It also means that people who have a mortgage, or CD account have a higher chance of taking personal loan.

The following coefficients are negative

  • Age, ZIPCode, Securities_Account, Online, CreditCard
  • This means that younger people a more likely to take personal loans, older customers are less likely.
  • Certain zip codes are less likely to take personal loans.
  • People who are usually online tend to not take personal loans - so invest in face-to-face interaction at the bank.
  • People who have securities account are less likely to take personal loans, so do not cross-sell to them.
  • People who have credit cards from other banks are less likely to take personal loans, perhaps because their short term loan needs are met by the credit cards.

More interpretation of the coefficients in terms of change of odds¶

Not all features have the same impact.

  • CD_Account - This has the most impact. If someone gets a CD account with the bank, it increases the odds of the person asking for a personal loan by 2501%.
  • Education - This has the second largest impact at 388% increase in odds.
  • Family - Family size is the third-largest impactful variable with increase in odds 102% for each additional member in the family.
  • online - This is the fourth largest impact - and is a negative impact. People who are online are 40% less likely to take personal loans.

The remaining features have a much smaller impact on the overall odds of taking a personal loan.

Recommendation to Bank based on Logistic Regression¶

Given the analysis, we make the following recommendations

  1. Target all customers who have a CD account since they are the most likely to take a personal loan.
  2. Target people will graduate degrees or higher in campaigns/fliers, and direct face-to-face contact.
  3. Instead of spending time targeting singles, focus more on people with families, especially having at least one or more kids.
  4. Pay attention to the people who visit the bank for regular teller transactions rather than using online options. Have managers engage with them since they are more likely to take a personal loan.

Observation¶

Although we got a fairly high number for the precision on the test data (0.83), the model is clearly overfitted since the precision is 1.0 for the training data. Also, there is a big difference between the precision number obtained from the training data vs. that obtained from the testing data.

This is because decision trees are prone to overfitting unless controlled.

def plotDecisionTree(model, feature_names):
    '''
    Utility function to simplify plotting of decision tree
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 30))
    out = tree.plot_tree(
            model,
            feature_names=feature_names,
            filled=True,
            fontsize=9,
            node_ids=False,
            class_names=None,
    )
    plt.show()

# We will use GridSearchCV with different hyperparametes to come up with a smaller depth for the tree
# GridSearchCV needs a set of objects, which we will now create step by step before using that function.

# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight={0: 0.15, 1: 0.85})

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(1, 5),
    "criterion": ["gini"], 
    "splitter": ["best", "random"],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.000001, 0.00001, 0.0001],
    "max_features": ["sqrt"],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Run the grid search to find the best combination
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Set the CLF to the best combination of parameters - this becomes the new decision tree model
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
estimator.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# New training is now complete

The important features are the same but the Income has been given the highest priority by the decision tree compared to the Logistic Regression model.

Recommendation to Bank based on Decision Tree¶

Given the analysis, we make the following recommendations

  1. Target the higher income customers, no matter what other characteristics or banking patterns they have. Given the model, the highest earners also have the highest likelihood of taking out personal loans.
  2. Target people will graduate degrees or higher in campaigns/fliers, and direct face-to-face contact.
  3. If you need to choose people to target based on family size, instead of spending time targeting singles, focus more on people with families, especially having at least one or more kids.
  4. Target all customers who have a CD account since they are more likely to take a personal loan.
  5. Target older people more in your campaigns rather than younger ones.

Comparison of results from logistic regression and decision tree¶

The results between the logistic regressions and decision tree are somewhat similar with some key difference.

Dissimilarities of the models¶
  • Whereas logistic regression model siad that people with CS accounts have the highest likelihood to taking personal loans, the decision tree model gave the highest importance to the people with higher incomes.
  • LG asked us to give importance to people who visit the bank and not do online banking, but DT says that online banking is not significant.
Contradiction between the models¶
  • The major contradiction is that LG says that older people are less likely to take loans whereas DT says that older people are more likely to take loans.
Similarities of the models¶
  • Both models agree that education level, family size, and CD Account, and to some extent zip code, have a positive impact on increasing likelihood of taking out personal loans.
